mbitions, and new notions of married life provides a vivid sense of urban modernity. She argues that the radical social transformations associated with post-1857 urban restructuring, and the political flux resulting from social reform, Gandhian nationalism, communalism, Partition, and the Cold War shaped the realm of the intimate as much as the public sphere. Love and friendship, notions of privacy, attitudes to women's work, and relationships within households are among the book's major themes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and towns in literature. 0aCivilization, Modern, in literature. 0aHindi fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHindi fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2019z978311149143140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847607040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438476070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438476070/original  a978-3-11-149143-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles